[accomplishment]
title=First Autopilot Testcase
description=The Ubuntu Quality Team has accepted your first Autopilot testcase
collection=ubuntu-community
category=QA
needs-signing=true
icon=devel.png
needs-information=launchpad-email
summary = To ensure a great quality around Ubuntu(and its flavors), manual and automatic tests are used. Autopilot tests run against unity and graphical components to ensure correct behavior on common situations.
steps: Create a <a href="https://help.launchpad.net/YourAccount/NewAccount/">Launchpad</a> Account.
    Configure and run an <a href="https://wiki.ubuntu.com/UsingDevelopmentReleases/OtherWays">Ubuntu development instance</a>.
    Add the «ppa:autopilot/ppa» repository
    Install «bzr, libautopilot-qt, python-autopilot»
    <a href="https://wiki.ubuntu.com/QATeam/ContributingTestcases/Launchpad">Configure</a> your environment.
    <a href="https://wiki.ubuntu.com/QATeam/ContributingTestcases/Autopilot">Write an Autopilot testcase</a>.
    Merge the Autopilot testcase into https://launchpad.net/ubuntu-autopilot-tests
links: https://wiki.ubuntu.com/QATeam/ContributingTestcases/Autopilot
    http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=qD_e_xqlBbg
tips = Prioritaze our <a href="https://bugs.launchpad.net/ubuntu-autopilot-tests/+bugs?field.tag=todo">todo list</a> if you're unsure on what to work on.
     Improve current testcases instead of create new ones.
     Say hello at #ubuntu-autopilot or present yourself in the <a href="https://lists.ubuntu.com/mailman/listinfo/ubuntu-quality">quality mailing list</a>.
     Assist to a <a href="https://wiki.ubuntu.com/QATeam/Hackfest">Hackfest</a>.
pitfalls = Start writing an Autopilot testcase without assigning to yourself an <a href="https://bugs.launchpad.net/ubuntu-autopilot-tests/+bugs?field.tag=todo">open report</a>(if available).
    Create an Autopilot testcase based on an application running in a released Ubuntu version.
help = #ubuntu-quality, #ubuntu-autopilot on Freenode
author = Javier Lopez <chilicuil@ubuntu.com>
